node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Good News Movement on September 15, 2021. May be an image of ocean and text that says 'UK introduces shark fin ban making it illegal to import or export fins or create products from them good news! MOVEMENT'.

node.text: Though shark finning in the UK has been banned in UK waters since 2013, loopholes allowed the UK to still be part of the global trade. For example, it was still legal to import 25 kg of shark fin into the UK for ‘personal consumption’. Now, a more comprehensive law will prohibit that. Animal welfare minister Lord Goldsmith announced: “Shark finning is indescribably cruel and causes thousands of shark to die terrible deaths. It is also unforgivably wasteful. The practice is rightly banned in UK waters, but the trade continues, with serious implications for the future of these magnificent creatures.” He continued: “That is why we are now banning the import both of detached shark fins and shark fin products. Our action will not only help boost shark numbers, it will send a clear message that we do not support an industry that is forcing many species to the brink of extinction.” Currently 143 shark species are listed as ‘under threat’ by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN). On June 8, the U.S. passed the Shark Fin Sales Elimination Act (S. 1106) — a bill that bans the buying and selling of shark fins in the United States.

Retired flight attendant Paul Veneto of Braintree Massachusetts has successfully completed a 220 mile trek from Boston to NYC pushing a beverage cart ... a tribute to flight attendants and passengers who lost their lives 20 years ago today. Funds raised will be split between donations to families of those who lost their life & Power Forward 25, an organization that helps those struggling with addiction, a battle he knows first-hand. Swipe right for video of trek.
Let's congratulate @pauliespush ... you're amazing Paulie!!! You make us all proud. 🇺🇸 ❤
Video and photo: @compelpictures
